subanswer.text: A prime number has exactly two distinct positive divisors: $1$ and itself. Therefore, any other positive integer must be the square of a prime number. This is because if it were not a perfect square, it would have more than three factors: 1, its square root, the number itself, and at least one more factor greater than its square root. Hence, such a number has exactly three distinct positive divisors: 1, its square root, and the number itself. The answer is the square of a prime number.
